{
  "texts": [
    "The distinction between system and environment represents a paradox.",
    "The paradox lies in the fact that a system must be separate from its environment to maintain its operations and identity, but it also relies on interactions with the environment to sustain itself.",
    "Following both Luhmann (1995) and Spencer Brown (1969), a distinction-a system-is distinct but paradoxically in unity with its environment.",
    "The means by which a system stabilizes or maintains its own paradoxical ontology-i.e., its identity-is through re-entry (Spencer Brown 1969) or recursion, or what Maturana and Varela (1980) and subsequently Luhmann (1995) conceptualized as self-referential operational closure-autopoiesis.",
    "A system's environment (or from Spencer Brown's perspective the unmarked state) is understood as a condition of infinite possibility or indeterminacy within which a systemic distinction is an ordering of indeterminacy."
  ]
}